 Business Briefs
																								 London, Oct. 28: The second-round bid for Ford Motors Jaguar and Land Rover is due tomorrow. The Tata group is in the race for the British marques. Sources said there were six contenders at present and the number is likely to be narrowed down to two. The Tatas are expected to lead the race, but will face stiff competition from jp Morgan, according to The Sunday Times. 																								 New Delhi, Oct. 28: The government is likely to take a decision on the State Bank of Indias proposal to raise about Rs 18,000 crore through a rights issue in the next 15 days. The issue is awaiting the finance ministers approval. After this, the proposal will be placed before the cabinet, which is likely to be done before Parliament begins its Winter Session, official sources said.																								 Calcutta, Oct. 28: Bharat Earth Movers Ltd (beml) will pick up a 48 per cent stake and Coal India Ltd and Damodar Valley Corporation will have 26 per cent each in the special purpose vehicle for the closed public sector Mining and Allied Machinery Corporation.																								 New Delhi, Oct. 28: Industry body cii has asked the government to announce the roadmap for goods and services tax, proposed to come into effect from 2010, with a suitable model based on efficient tax administration and lower cost of compliance to the taxpayers.																								 Mumbai, Oct. 28: IDBI Bank plans to launch a business model by the year-end to increase lending to small and medium enterprises (sme). The project aims to set up 75 sme centres in the country, which will be headed by an officer of the rank of assistant general manager.																								 New Delhi, Oct. 28: India will seek additional liquefied natural gas from Qatar to meet its growing energy needs when petroleum minister Murli Deora visits Doha tomorrow. Deora will also pitch for a gas-based petrochemical plant to be set up by Indian firms.																								 New Delhi, Oct. 28:The Government has sought legal opinion on the GMR groups funding structure for the Rs 9,000-crore modernisation plan of the Delhi airport.

